Human bocavirus, a new pathogen of childhood: Background
-----------------------------------------------
In 2001, Allander et al. described an innovative molecular method for
discovery of previously unknown viral agents in serum or plasma samples,
incorporating DNase treatment and its application to the identification of
2 novel virus species. The method is based on DNase treatment of serum
followed by restriction enzyme digestion and sequence-independent single
primer amplification of the fragments. Experimental validation of the
method confirmed that both DNA and RNA viruses could be reproducibly
identified at concentrations of approximately 10(6) genome equivalents per
ml in 50 micro liters of serum. In the initial application of the method, 2
previously unknown parvoviruses were discovered in bovine sera used as
diluent. These 2 novel parvoviruses proved to be frequent contaminants of
bovine sera (see: Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A. 2001 Sep 25;98(20):11609-14.
Epub 2001 Sep 18).
Application of this methodology has now identified a novel human pathogen
of childhood. A preliminary description was reported by Reuters on 22 Aug
2005 (see ProMED-mail post: Human bocavirus, a new pathogen of childhood
20050823.2487), and a full description is now available in the 23 Aug 2005
Early Edition of Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences USA
<http://www.pnas.org/cgi/content/abstract/0504666102v1?etoc>.
The abstract of the paper by Tobias Allander et al., entitled "Cloning of a
human parvovirus by molecular screening of respiratory tract samples,"
states the following: "The identification of new virus species is a key
issue for the study of infectious disease but is technically very
difficult. We developed a system for large-scale molecular virus screening
of clinical samples based on host DNA depletion, random PCR amplification,
large-scale sequencing, and bioinformatics. The technology was applied to
pooled human respiratory tract samples. The 1st experiments detected 7
human virus species without the use of any specific reagent. Among the
detected viruses were one coronavirus and one parvovirus, both of which
were at that time uncharacterized. The parvovirus, provisionally named
human bocavirus, was in a retrospective clinical study detected in 17
additional patients and associated with lower respiratory tract infections
in children. The molecular virus screening procedure provides a general
culture-independent solution to the problem of detecting unknown virus
species in single or pooled samples. We suggest that a systematic
exploration of the viruses that infect humans, 'the human virome,' can be
initiated."
Parvoviruses are among the smallest, simplest eukaryotic viruses. They are
widespread in nature. Essentially, they fall into 2 groups: defective
viruses, which are dependent on helper virus for replication, and
autonomous and replication-competent viruses. In all, more than 50
parvoviruses have been identified. The family is divided into 2
subfamilies: the subfamily _Parvovirinae_ comprises 5 genera of vertebrate
viruses (_Parvovirus_, _Erythrovirus_, _Dependovirus_ , _Amdovirus_ and
_Bocavirus_). The genus _Bocavirus_ comprises 3 species; the previously
recognized _Bovine parvovirus_ and _Canine minute virus_, and now the newly
discovered Human bocavirus. The genomes of these viruses are linear,
single-stranded monopartite DNA, about 5.5 kb long with hairpin loops at
both ends of the genome. The hairpin structures at both ends of the genome
are characteristic of the sub-family _Parvovirinae_. The virions are
isometric (icosahedral), not enveloped, 18-26 nm in diameter, with 60 units
of the capsid protein. The viruses classified in the 5 genera are
phylogenetically distinct.
--
