Source: BBC News online, Sun 21 Aug 2005 [edited]
<http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/4163846.stm>

Discovery of Unique Chest Infection Virus
-----------------------------------------------
Scientists have identified a unique virus linked to serious chest
infections in children and babies. All of the 17 children with what the
researchers are calling human bocavirus had distressed breathing and fever
and were hospitalized. In most cases, the virus causing the lower
respiratory tract infection is known; most commonly, it is respiratory
syncytial virus. But in around 1/3rd of cases, no obvious pathogen is
found. Dr. Tobias Allander and colleagues at the Karolinska University
Hospital in Stockholm tested 378 respiratory tract samples collected from
patients in the hospital who had chest infections for which no obvious
cause had been found.
Rather than looking for well known viruses, the team used technology
similar to that used to crack the code of human DNA in the Human Genome
Project to see what viruses were present. They detected 7 virus species in
the samples, one of which was a parvovirus that had never
been characterized before, which they called human bocavirus
(HBoV). All of these samples containing HBoV had come from children or infants.
The researchers then checked for the virus in 540 children with lower
respiratory tract infections being treated in the hospital. In the 17
children found to have HBoV, this virus was the only one present,
suggesting that it was indeed the cause of their illness. Although the
findings will not directly change the way childhood chest infections are
treated in the short-term, the researchers say their findings are important.
Dr. Allander said: "This is quite a prevalent virus, and it has remained
undetected until now. It tells us that there is a lot we do not know. Also,
maybe this virus, which is a parvovirus, can cause other conditions." He
said it was likely there were many more viruses yet to be discovered but
that are causing illness in humans. "Finding these might be important for
treating disease," he said. He urged scientists to search for more of these
unrecognized viruses.
Dr. Maria Zambon, a virologist at the Health Protection Agency, said the
detection was welcome. "The detection of human bocavirus is the latest in a
long line of recently discovered respiratory viruses." And she added: "The
sort of molecular detection methods used to uncover human bocavirus will
undoubtedly lead to the discovery of more viruses in the coming years." Dr.
Warren Lenney of the British Thoracic Society said: "We need to know more
about the cause of infections in the respiratory tract, and this research
helps us with this. One of the difficulties, however, is that even though
viruses are isolated from nasopharyngeal specimens, we cannot be sure that
they are responsible for problems that occur lower down in the lung.
--
